USA Gymnastics supports the statement of the United States Olympic Committee and recognizes that it is imperative that the Olympic family foster a safe environment for all of our athletes.
We coincided with the declaration of the USOC that the interests of the athletes, the clubs and their sports, can be better served by making significant changes within our organization, rather than withdrawing certifications.
USA Gymnastics supports an independent investigation that can shed light on how the abuse that the survivors of Larry Nassar described with such courage could have gone unseen for so long and accepts any necessary and appropriate changes.
The goal of USA Gymnastics and the U.S. Olympic Committee is the same: to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible for athletes to pursue their dreams in a protected, positive and empowered environment.
During the 1960s, Brzezinski worked for John F. Kennedy as an advisor and, subsequently, for the government of Lyndon B. Johnson.
He advised Carter on foreign policy in the 1976 elections. Subsequently, he worked as a national security advisor (NSA) between 1977 and 1981, after Henry Kissinger.
As a national security advisor, he assisted Carter in the diplomatic management of international affairs, such as the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between the United States and China at the end of the 1970s, the Iranian Revolution of 1979, which led to a hostage crisis in Iran, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
